      <body>
         <div>

            <p>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-1a.1" xml:lang="en">[...] practising this, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-1a.2" xml:lang="en">how would one not become a king?” </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-1a.3" xml:lang="en">Confucius said: </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-1a.4" xml:lang="en">“Poetry has no hidden (=left unexpressed) intent, [ </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-1a.5" xml:lang="en">music has no hidden emotions, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-1a.6" xml:lang="en">documents (characters?) have no hidden meaning.” </seg>
                </p>

            <p>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-2a.1" xml:lang="en">[at the time when ...](?), </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-2a.2" xml:lang="en">King Wen had received the mandate. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-2a.3" xml:lang="en">The eulogies are (about) equalizing virtue, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-2a.4" xml:lang="en">they mention often (the term) “later”, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-2a.5" xml:lang="en">their music is quiet and slow, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-2a.6" xml:lang="en">their songs dignified and at ease, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-2a.7" xml:lang="en">their thought deep and far reaching, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-2a.8" xml:lang="en">this is perfection! </seg>
                </p>

            <p>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-3a.1" xml:lang="en">The Great Xia are about the fullness of virtue, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-3a.2" xml:lang="en">they often talk about [...] </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-3a.3" xml:lang="en">[The small Xia] are about [virtue]; </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-3a.4" xml:lang="en">they often talk about [things that are difficult and grievous], </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-3a.5" xml:lang="en">(the virtue of the rulers) is sad and small. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-3a.6" xml:lang="en">The airs of the states, their acceptance of things (range of things described) is wide, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-3a.7" xml:lang="en">they observe the costumes of the people, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-3a.8" xml:lang="en">they greatly collect talent, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-3a.9" xml:lang="en">their words are patterned, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-3a.10" xml:lang="en">their sound beautiful. </seg>
                </p>

            <p>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-4a.1" xml:lang="en">Confucius said: </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-4a.2" xml:lang="en">“Who could [...] </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-4a.3" xml:lang="en">He said: </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-4a.4" xml:lang="en">“Are not the Odes like a fair gate? </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-4a.5" xml:lang="en">When one is together with low status people and gives expression to them [their innermost feelings], </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-4a.6" xml:lang="en">how should be one’s way of employing one’s mind (=how can one deal with it)? </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-4a.7" xml:lang="en">He said: </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-4a.8" xml:lang="en">[originally explained as 也- see 讀本 1:15 n.9] . “The airs of the States” are such [=they tell you how to achieve this]. </seg>
                </p>

            <p>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-5a.1" xml:lang="en">When the people are worried and troubled, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-5a.2" xml:lang="en">and those above and below are not in harmony, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-5a.3" xml:lang="en">how can one deal with it? </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-5a.4" xml:lang="en"> </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-5a.5" xml:lang="en">[...] [when the country and the leaders] have success, how [can one deal with it]? </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-5a.6" xml:lang="en">He said: </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-5a.7" xml:lang="en">“The Eulogies are like this.” </seg>
                </p>

            <p>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-6a.1" xml:lang="en">The “pure temple” Mao 266) is about the virtue of the king, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-6a.2" xml:lang="en">it is perfect. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-6a.3" xml:lang="en">To treat respectfully the rituals of the ancestral temple, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-6a.4" xml:lang="en">to build their foundation; </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-6a.5" xml:lang="en">to possess a fine virtue (Mao 266.1) </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-6a.6" xml:lang="en">to build their substance, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-6a.7" xml:lang="en">“solemn and (concordant=) acting in unison are the illustrious assistants” (ibid.), </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-6a.8" xml:lang="en">to build its [...] </seg>
                </p>

            <p>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-7a.1" xml:lang="en">[Di told king Wen] </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-7a.2" xml:lang="en">"[I] think cherishingly of your bright virtue” (Mao 241.13), </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-7a.3" xml:lang="en">what (does it mean)? </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-7a.4" xml:lang="en">It is really telling him. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-7a.5" xml:lang="en">“The appointment came from Heaven, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-7a.6" xml:lang="en">it gave the appointment to this King Wen” (Mao 236.6), </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-7a.7" xml:lang="en">what (does it mean)? </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-7a.8" xml:lang="en">It is really giving an order to him, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-7a.9" xml:lang="en">it is true. </seg>
                </p>

            <p>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-8a.1" xml:lang="en">Confucius said: </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-8a.2" xml:lang="en">“This is the mandate. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-8a.3" xml:lang="en">could king Wen, even if he wanted, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-8a.4" xml:lang="en">get (it) (just by his own will?). </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-8a.5" xml:lang="en">This is the mandate. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-8a.6" xml:lang="en">“The ten month” (Mao 193) excels in words of blame. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-8a.7" xml:lang="en">“The rain has no rule” (Mao 194) and “Crest-like is the Southern mountain” (Mao 191) all talk about the decadence of those above, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-8a.8" xml:lang="en">kings and dukes are feel shame for it. </seg>
                </p>

            <p>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-9a.1" xml:lang="en">In “The small calamity” (Mao 195) [the ruler] has many doubts, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-9a.2" xml:lang="en">doubting that the words (of his advisors) will not fit his aims; </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-9a.3" xml:lang="en">in ‘Small and minute” (Mao 196) the words are not wicked, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-9a.4" xml:lang="en">not having much cunning. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-9a.5" xml:lang="en">In Xiao Bian (Mao 197) and in “Skilled words” (Mao 198), he talks about the damage of the slanderers. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-9a.6" xml:lang="en">In “cutting the wood” (Mao 165) [..] </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-9a.7" xml:lang="en">he truly blames himself. </seg>
                </p>

            <p>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-10a.1" xml:lang="en">In “Heaven protects” (Mao 166) the blessings that he obtains are limitless, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-10a.2" xml:lang="en">because he complies with the virtue of the lord. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-10a.3" xml:lang="en">The criticism of “Minister of war” (Mao 185) </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-10a.4" xml:lang="en">has also its reasons. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-10a.5" xml:lang="en">In “The yellow bird” (Mao 187) he is distressed and wants to return to his old land, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-10a.6" xml:lang="en">isn’t it because the many humiliations make him feel sick? </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-10a.7" xml:lang="en">In “Luxuriantly grows the aster-southernwood” (Mao 176) one grows thanks to others. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-10a.8" xml:lang="en">In "Splendid are the flowers" (Mao 214) [...] </seg>
                </p>

            <p>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-11a.1" xml:lang="en">The change in “Guan ju” (Mao 1), </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-11a.2" xml:lang="en">the time in “Jiu mu” (Mao 4), </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-11a.3" xml:lang="en">the wisdom of “Han Guang” (Mao 9), </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-11a.4" xml:lang="en">the return of “Que chao” (Mao 12), </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-11a.5" xml:lang="en">the retribution of “Gan tang” (Mao 16), </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-11a.6" xml:lang="en">the thoughts of “The green jacket” (Mao 27), </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-11a.7" xml:lang="en">the emotions of “Yan yan” (Mao 28), </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-11a.8" xml:lang="en">What about them? </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-11a.9" xml:lang="en">He said: </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-11a.10" xml:lang="en">[once the emotions are stirred, in each case they can be better than when they just started]. </seg>
                </p>

            <p>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-12a.1" xml:lang="en">“Guan ju” (Mao 1) uses sexual desire to illustrate [...] towards the rites. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-12a.2" xml:lang="en">[...] two. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-12a.3" xml:lang="en">The fourth stanza develops an analogy with the pleasure [derived from the] qin and se instruments, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-12a.4" xml:lang="en">comparing it with the desire of sexual fulfillment. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-12a.5" xml:lang="en">By means of the joy [derived from] bells and drums [...] </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-12a.6" xml:lang="en">[...] pleasure, bringing it back to the rites, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-12a.7" xml:lang="en">is this not [a case of] being able to make a change [of attitude]? </seg>
                </p>

            <p>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-13a.1" xml:lang="en">In “Jiu mu” (Mao 4) the fortune indeed resides in the gentleman, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-13a.2" xml:lang="en">is it not [...]? </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-13a.3" xml:lang="en">In “Han Guang” (Mao 9) [...] </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-13a.4" xml:lang="en">[one does not look after what one cannot] obtain, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-13a.5" xml:lang="en">one does not exhaust himself after what one is not able to accomplish, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-13a.6" xml:lang="en">is this not understanding what is constant? </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-13a.7" xml:lang="en">In“Que chao” (Mao 12) he sends out one hundred carts, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-13a.8" xml:lang="en">is this not [a case of] having a [proper] mate? </seg>
                </p>

            <p>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-14a.1" xml:lang="en">“Gan tang” (Mao 16) [...] </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-14a.2" xml:lang="en">reaches to the proper man, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-14a.3" xml:lang="en">respectfully loves his tree, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-14a.4" xml:lang="en">his retribution is great. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-14a.5" xml:lang="en">The love of “Gan tang” </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-14a.6" xml:lang="en">is because of Duke Shao [...]. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-14a.7" xml:lang="en">[...] feeling of love. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-14a.8" xml:lang="en">The change of “Guan ju”, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-14a.9" xml:lang="en">such thought [longing] is advantageous [=reflecting on this change of attitude can lead to improve one’s own behavior]. </seg>
                </p>

            <p>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-15a.1" xml:lang="en">The time of “Jiu mu”, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-15a.2" xml:lang="en">it is because of its fortune (?). </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-15a.3" xml:lang="en">The wisdom in “Han Guang”, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-15a.4" xml:lang="en">is to know what cannot be obtained. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-15a.5" xml:lang="en">The coming back [=being given in marriage] of “Que chao”, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-15a.6" xml:lang="en">it is because of her partner [..]. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-15a.7" xml:lang="en">Duke Shao. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-15a.8" xml:lang="en">The grief of “The green jacket”, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-15a.9" xml:lang="en">is because of thinking about the ancients. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-15a.10" xml:lang="en">The emotions of “Yan yan”, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-15a.11" xml:lang="en">are because of his solitude. </seg>
                </p>

            <p>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-16a.1" xml:lang="en">Confucius said: </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-16a.2" xml:lang="en">“In “Ge Tan” (Mao 2) </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-16a.3" xml:lang="en">I get a poem that respects the beginning [=honors the origins], </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-16a.4" xml:lang="en">the character of the people is originally like this. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-16a.5" xml:lang="en">Looking at its beauty </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-16a.6" xml:lang="en">one necessarily desires to revert to its root. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-16a.7" xml:lang="en">Now, that the creeper is sung about, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-16a.8" xml:lang="en">it’s because of fine and coarse dolichos clothes [that can be made out of it] . </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-16a.9" xml:lang="en">That Hou Ji is honored, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-16a.10" xml:lang="en">it’s because of the virtue of [his descendents] Wen and Wu. </seg>
                </p>

            <p>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-17a.1" xml:lang="en">Through “Gan tang” (Mao 16) </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-17a.2" xml:lang="en">I obtain the respect of the ancestral temple, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-17a.3" xml:lang="en">the character of the people is originally like this. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-17a.4" xml:lang="en">If one values a man, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-17a.5" xml:lang="en">one necessarily [therefore] respect his position; </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-17a.6" xml:lang="en">if one rejoices in a man, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-17a.7" xml:lang="en">one necessarily [therefore] like what he did. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-17a.8" xml:lang="en">It is the same for disliking a man. </seg>
                </p>

            <p>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-18a.1" xml:lang="en">[...] [From “Mugua,” I obtained the reason why] [offerings of] money and silk [=offerings] cannot be rejected, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-18a.2" xml:lang="en">the character of the people is originally like this. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-18a.3" xml:lang="en">nner intents must have something through which they are expressed, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-18a.4" xml:lang="en">words must have something through which they are conveyed </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-18a.5" xml:lang="en">and [only] then [they are] accepted, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-18a.6" xml:lang="en">something must be presented </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-18a.7" xml:lang="en">in order to establish a relationship, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-18a.8" xml:lang="en">[so that] others will not be able to reject it. </seg>
                </p>

            <p>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-19a.1" xml:lang="en">In “Mu Gua” there is an inner wish </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-19a.2" xml:lang="en">and [the song's persona] does not get to express it. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-19a.3" xml:lang="en">Establishing relationships [...] </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-19a.4" xml:lang="en">What about “Di du”? </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-19a.5" xml:lang="en">In this way he [=the lord] confers ranks. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-19a.6" xml:lang="en">When he [=the gentleman] is separated from what he loves [=honor and rank], </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-19a.7" xml:lang="en">he must necessarily say: </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-19a.8" xml:lang="en">How could I give it up?” </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-19a.9" xml:lang="en">This is the conferring of gifts to guests. </seg>
                </p>

            <p>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-20a.1" xml:lang="en">Confucius said: </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-20a.2" xml:lang="en">from “The cricket” (Mao 114) one understands fear; </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-20a.3" xml:lang="en">from “The locusts” (Mao 5) [one understands] the gentleman. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-20a.4" xml:lang="en">n “The northern wind” (Mao 41) [the song's persona] does not break off [feelings], </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-20a.5" xml:lang="en">as [it happens] for men’s resentment. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-20a.6" xml:lang="en">In “Zi jin” (Mao 91) he does not [...] </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-20a.7" xml:lang="en">Before the east was bright” (Mao 100) has a propitious beginning. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-20a.8" xml:lang="en">The words of “Jiang Zhong” (Mao 76), </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-20a.9" xml:lang="en">cannot but be feared. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-20a.10" xml:lang="en">In “Yang zhi shui” (Mao 68) his loving his wife is ardent; </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-20a.11" xml:lang="en">in “Cai Ge’ (Mao 72) the love of the wife [...] </seg>
                </p>

            <p>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-21a.1" xml:lang="en">“Lu ming” (Mao 169) starts with joy, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-21a.2" xml:lang="en">and there is a banquet to establish relationships, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-21a.3" xml:lang="en">people see the good and imitate it, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-21a.4" xml:lang="en">it ends with unsatisfied people. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-21a.5" xml:lang="en">In “The rabbit nests” (Mao 6) he uses people’s (talents), </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-21a.6" xml:lang="en">then I will take [...] </seg>
                </p>

            <p>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-22a.1" xml:lang="en">[...] “[Junzi] yang yang” (Mao 67) is about petty people. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-22a.2" xml:lang="en">“You tu” (Mao 70) is about not meeting the right time. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-22a.3" xml:lang="en">The last stanza of “Large are the fields” (Mao 212) </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-22a.4" xml:lang="en">knows (how to use) words and has ritual propriety. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-22a.5" xml:lang="en">“Xiao ming” (Mao 207) does not [...] </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-22a.6" xml:lang="en">loyal. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-22a.7" xml:lang="en">“The boat of cypress wood” (Mao 26) is gloomy, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-22a.8" xml:lang="en">“Gu feng” (Mao 35) is about rejection, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-22a.9" xml:lang="en">“Liao e” (Mao 202) has filial intent, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-22a.10" xml:lang="en">“Xi you chang chu” (Mao 148) is about obtaining </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-22a.11" xml:lang="en">and making plans for something. </seg>
                </p>

            <p>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-23a.1" xml:lang="en">Loathing without compassion. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-23a.2" xml:lang="en">“Qiang you ci” (Mao 46) is about being careful about secrets </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-23a.3" xml:lang="en">and not knowing how to speak [about them], </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-23a.4" xml:lang="en">“Qing ying” (Mao 219) knows [...] </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-23a.5" xml:lang="en">[...] disgrace and not knowing others. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-23a.6" xml:lang="en">In “Crossing the Zhen” (Mao 87) [the song's persona] is breaking off an accommodating [relationship] and serving as an official. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-23a.7" xml:lang="en">“Jiaozhen” (Mao 124) is about a widow. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-23a.8" xml:lang="en">“Heshui” (Mao 183?) is about knowing [...] </seg>
                </p>

            <p>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-24a.1" xml:lang="en">precious. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-24a.2" xml:lang="en">As for the commotion in “Jiang dache,” (Mao 206) </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-24a.3" xml:lang="en">there is nothing else that he could have done. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-24a.4" xml:lang="en">As for the excesses in “Zhanlu,” (Mao 174) </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-24a.5" xml:lang="en">do those men still appear intoxicated? </seg>
                </p>

            <p>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-25a.1" xml:lang="en">Confucius said: </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-25a.2" xml:lang="en">“Wanqiu,” (Mao 136) I commend it. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-25a.3" xml:lang="en">“Yijie,” (Mao 106) I delight in it. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-25a.4" xml:lang="en">“Shijiu,” (Mao 152) I trust it. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-25a.5" xml:lang="en">“Wenwang,” (Mao 235) I admire it. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-25a.6" xml:lang="en">“Qingmiao,” (Mao 266) I respect it. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-25a.7" xml:lang="en">“Liewen,” (Mao 269) I take joy in it. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-25a.8" xml:lang="en">“Haotian you chengming,” (Mao 271) I [.] it. </seg>
                </p>

            <p>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-26a.1" xml:lang="en">“Wanqiu” (Mao 136) says: </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-26a.2" xml:lang="en">“It truly has affection, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-26a.3" xml:lang="en">yet it is without prestige.” (????) </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-26a.4" xml:lang="en">I commend it. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-26a.5" xml:lang="en">“Yijie” (Mao 106) says: </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-26a.6" xml:lang="en">“four arrows return, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-26a.7" xml:lang="en">use [them] to defend [against] the chaos.” </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-26a.8" xml:lang="en">I delight in it. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-26a.9" xml:lang="en">“Shijiu” (Mao 152) says: </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-26a.10" xml:lang="en">“Their attitude is consistent, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-26a.11" xml:lang="en">and their minds are so concentrated.” </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-26a.12" xml:lang="en">I trust it. </seg>
                </p>

            <p>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-27a.1" xml:lang="en">“Wenwang” (Mao 235) says: </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-27a.2" xml:lang="en">“King Wen is above, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-27a.3" xml:lang="en">shining in the sky!” </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-27a.4" xml:lang="en">I admire it. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-27a.5" xml:lang="en">“Qingmiao” (Mao 266) says: </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-27a.6" xml:lang="en">“Solemn and harmonious are the distinguished assistants; </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-27a.7" xml:lang="en">There are a great many officials, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-27a.8" xml:lang="en">who cherish the virtue of King Wen.” </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-27a.9" xml:lang="en">I respect it. </seg>
                </p>

            <p>
                    <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-28a.1" xml:lang="en">“Liewen” (Mao 269) says: </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-28a.2" xml:lang="en">“Do not compete with people, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-28a.3" xml:lang="en">the virtue is great and distinguished, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-28a.4" xml:lang="en">“Woo hoo! The former kings were not forgotten.” </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-28a.5" xml:lang="en">I take joy in this. </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-28a.6" xml:lang="en">“Great Heaven owns our fixed destiny, </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-28a.7" xml:lang="en">and the two former kings received it.” (Mao 271) </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-28a.8" xml:lang="en">It is venerable and illustrious! </seg>
               <seg corresp="#KR2p0032_tls_001-28a.9" xml:lang="en">Eulogy” [...] </seg>
                </p>

         </div>
